The Architecture: "The Host & The DJs"
The Host (Server): One person clicks "Go Live." Their PC broadcasts the audio.

The Community (DJs): Friends tune in via the Ngrok link. Their web player has a special "Add to Queue" button.

The Magic: When a friend uploads a song (or pastes a Suno ID), it travels through the tunnel and lands directly in the Host's RADIO_QUEUE.

This makes it interactive without costing you a dime in server fees.

Here is the plan to build the Suno On-Air Server with Community Uploads enabled.

Step 1: Install Dependencies
We need pyngrok to tunnel out to the internet and flask (or just robust http.server logic) to handle the file uploads. To keep it lightweight and dependency-free (standard library), we will stick to http.server but add a POST handler for uploads.

(No action needed if you stick to the prompt below, standard library is fine).

Step 2: The "Community Radio" Server Script
This script handles three things: Streaming Audio, Serving the Web Page, and Accepting Uploads from friends.

Copy and paste this prompt:

"I need to build the 'Suno On-Air' Radio Server with Community features. Please create a new file named radio_server.py.

1. The Server Setup:

Import http.server, socket, threading, os, random, shutil.

Create a global list PLAYLIST_QUEUE (list of file paths).

Create a global variable CURRENT_TRACK (path).

2. The Request Handler (The Brain):

Create a class RadioHandler(http.server.SimpleHTTPRequestHandler).

GET /: Serve a dynamic HTML page 'Suno Live Radio'.

UI: Dark Mode. Big Album Art. 'Now Playing' text.

Community Feature: A distinct 'Request Song' section. A File Input and 'Upload' button.

Player: <audio src="/stream.mp3" autoplay controls>.

GET /stream.mp3: Serve the bytes of CURRENT_TRACK. (Handle byte-range requests if possible, or just stream the file).

GET /status: Return JSON { title: "...", artist: "...", listeners: 12 } for the UI to auto-update.

POST /upload: Handle file uploads from listeners.

Save the uploaded MP3 to a local Radio_Requests folder.

Automatically add the new file path to PLAYLIST_QUEUE.

Return a success message: 'Track added to queue!'.

3. The Broadcast Controller:

Create a class RadioStation.

start_broadcast():

Start the HTTP server on port 8085.

Tunnel: Import pyngrok and run public_url = ngrok.connect(8085).public_url.

Return the public_url to the main app.

dj_loop(): A background thread that checks:

If song finished? Pop next song from PLAYLIST_QUEUE -> Set as CURRENT_TRACK.

If queue empty? Play a random song from the local Library (fallback).

4. Dependencies:

Ensure it uses pyngrok for the public link."

Step 3: The UI to "Go Live"
Now add the control panel in your app so you can start the station and see what people are queuing.

Copy and paste this prompt:

"I need the Radio Dashboard UI in my main app.

1. The 'Go Live' Button:

Add a 'Broadcast' icon button to the Sidebar or Top Bar.

2. The Station Manager Window:

When clicked, open a CTkToplevel window.

Header: 'Suno On-Air' with a big Red 'OFF AIR' badge.

Action: A 'Start Broadcast' button.

When clicked, run radio_server.start_broadcast().

Change badge to 'LIVE' (Green).

Show the Public Link (clickable/copyable).

3. The Live Queue (Community Interaction):

Add a CTkScrollableFrame showing the PLAYLIST_QUEUE.

Real-time Updates: When a friend uploads a song via the web link, this list must update to show the new track.

Controls: Add 'Skip' and 'Kick' (remove from queue) buttons next to each track."